Linked Comprehension type

Passage-I

Bicyclo compounds are named by using the alkane name to designate the total number of carbon and bicycle is used as prefix. While naming the bicycloalkane we write an expression between the word bicycle and alkane (in square bracket), that denotes the number of carbon atoms in each bridge. The numerals are written in descending

order and the numbers are separated by full stops.

Passage-II

Although most of the IUPAC rules of open chain compounds are applied to alicyclic compounds, certain points deserve special attention.

(i) In cycloalkenes, the numbering should be done in a direction that gives the lower number for the substituent

attached on the double bond. 

(ii) In case the alicyclic compound has functional group I the ring as well as in the side chain, the compound is

considered as a derivative of that part in which principal functional group lies. On the basis of the following

seniority table for some of the principal groups, answer the questions given below.

colspan="2"></td></tr></table><p><strong>Linked Comprehension type</strong></p><table><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Passage-I</strong></p><p>Bicyclo compounds are named by using the alkane name to designate the total number of carbon and bicycle is used as prefix. While naming the bicycloalkane we write an expression between the word bicycle and alkane (in square bracket), that denotes the number of carbon atoms in each bridge. The numerals are written in descending</p><p>order and the numbers are separated by full stops.</p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>49.</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>The compound <img src="data:image/png;base64," />is known by which of the following name</p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td><p>a)</p></td><td><p>Bicyclo [2.2.2] octane</p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td><p>b)</p></td><td><p>Bicyclo [2.2.1] octane</p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td><p>c)</p></td><td><p>Bicyclo [2.2.1] heptane</p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td><p>d)</p></td><td><p>Bicyclo [2.1.2] heptane</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ans.</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>C</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sol.:</p></td><td colspan="2"></td></tr><tr><td><p>50.</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>The structure of bicycle [1.1.0] butane is</p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td><p>a)</p></td><td><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td><p>b)</p></td><td><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td><p>c)</p></td><td><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td><p>d)</p></td><td><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ans.</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>C</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sol.:</p></td><td colspan="2"></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Passage-II</strong></p><p>Although most of the IUPAC rules of open chain compounds are applied to alicyclic compounds, certain points deserve special attention.</p><p>(i) In cycloalkenes, the numbering should be done in a direction that gives the lower number for the substituent</p><p>attached on the double bond. </p><p>(ii) In case the alicyclic compound has functional group I the ring as well as in the side chain, the compound is</p><p>considered as a derivative of that part in which principal functional group lies.
